title: For Sale/Trade:  M76 8MM Sniper Rifle
postcontent: I'm consolidating calibers and looking to swap my M76 for a .308 long range semi auto setup. This rifle is in the same family as the Russian Druganov and is considered to be higher quality than the Romanian PSL rifle. This rifle is chambered in 8MM Mauser. It has an adjustable gas port which is a nice feature. I have put 80rds through this rifle and it's very fun and easy to shoot. I'd love to keep it but I am setup to shoot .308 and .30-06 and I find this gun doesn't get the attention it deserves. Includes (2) 10RD magazines, sling, original canvas scope cover. I'm open to trades. Looking for a long range .308 AR build. I already have a Remington 700 SPS tactical so not really interested in another bolt gun. I might consider a nice Springfield M1A1. Here's some technical data about the rifle:ZASTAVA M76 Yugoslav Sniper/Designated Marksman Rifle. Chambered in 7.92x57mm Mauser (a.k.a. 8x57mm IS).AK design w/ piston attached to bolt carrier. Milled forging receiver, longer and heavier AK-type rotating bolt, bolt carrier, barrel and other parts.Semi-automatic only, AK-type safety/selector on right side of receiver, w/ only 2 settings, 'safe' and 'fire'. Tapered barrel, operator-adjustable gas regulator. 10-round steel box magazine, w/ follower holding bolt opened after last shot. Scope: Original ZRAK ON-M76B 4x 5°10’. Elevation turret has bullet drop compensation markings. Optics side-rail permanently attached to receiver left wall. Scope can be removed, reattached with no loss of zero. Mechanically adjustable backup AKM-type iron sights with sliding tangent rear sight adjustable-100 m to 1,000 m. Accurate for a semi-automatic rifle. 1.5 Minute of Angle (MOA) consistent accuracy with appropriate ammunition against man sized targets achievable for average sniper at max. effective range of 800 meters (875 yards) and up to 1,000 m (1,094 yd) for excellent marksmen. Recoil is modest. Reliable and capable weapon with extensive combat service track record. (Source: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zastava_M76)
